Dataset Description:
(max. 75 words)

Our dataset includes numerous statistics about the Covid-19 pandemic in Austria since its beginning. Daily number of infections, hospitalization and deaths are available among different age groups. Moreover, all of the data is aggregatable by states and disctricts. Additionally, the dataset also includes vaccine, test and available hospital beds statistics.

Visualizations¶

Hypothesis 1¶

The number of deaths of COVID-19 patients is the highest in the 85+ group in all Austria.¶

Figure 1: Total number of COVID-19 deaths per 1000 inhabitants in Austria until 10.11.2022 by age group (source of data: dataset CovidFaelle_Altersgruppe.csv from https://covid19-dashboard.ages.at/).

Figure 2: Comulative number of COVID-19 deaths per 1000 inhabitants in Austria from 26.2.2020 until 10.11.2022 by age group (source of data: dataset CovidFaelle_Altersgruppe.csv from https://covid19-dashboard.ages.at/).

Hypothesis 2¶

The number of new daily Covid-19 infections in Austria does vary between seasons¶

Figure 3: Number of daily Covid-19 in Austria (source of data: CovidFaelle_Timeline_edited_2.csv from https://covid19-dashboard.ages.at/).

Figure 4: Number of Covid-19 infections by season in Austria (source of data: CovidFaelle_Timeline_edited_2.csv from https://covid19-dashboard.ages.at/).

Description¶

Hypothesis 1 Description¶

The aim of Figure 1 and 2 is to investigate the first hypothesis. The displayed data on both figures were normalized by the total number of inhabitants of each age group, excluding the possibility that the number of deaths in one age group would appear high only because it is the largest group. Both figures support the hypothesis that the number of deaths is the highest in the 85+ group.

Hypothesis 2 Description¶

Both visualisations support our hypothesis that daily Covid-19 infections do vary between seasons. It is clearly visible that there are temporal differences in the number of daily infections. In the first two years during the pandemic, in the winter months Covid infections did increase significantly compared to the warmer seasons. In the current year a new trend can be seen, that Covid infections arise in waves independent of the season.
